    <fr:title text="which bijection?">which <fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-00KR.xml" title="bijection" addr="jms-00KR" type="local">bijection</fr:link>?</fr:title>
    <fr:taxon>Remark</fr:taxon>
  </fr:frontmatter>
  <fr:mainmatter>
    <html:p>Although we are speaking of “being isomorphic” as the property of there being a <fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-00KR.xml" title="bijection" addr="jms-00KR" type="local">bijection</fr:link> between them, in practice, it is almost <html:em>never</html:em> useful to know that there exists some undetermined <fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-00KR.xml" title="bijection" addr="jms-00KR" type="local">bijection</fr:link> between given sets; it is always important to know <html:em>which</html:em> <fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-00KR.xml" title="bijection" addr="jms-00KR" type="local">bijection</fr:link>. Indeed, we have seen in <fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-00KT.xml" title="counting bijections between finite sets" addr="jms-00KT" type="local">Proposition <fr:contextual-number addr="jms-00KT" /></fr:link> that there can be many distinct <fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-00KR.xml" title="bijection" addr="jms-00KR" type="local">bijections</fr:link> between two sets.</html:p>
  </fr:mainmatter>
