                <fr:title text="isomorphic sets">isomorphic sets</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>Two sets <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex> are said to be <html:em><html:strong>isomorphic</html:strong></html:em> (and have the <html:em><html:strong>same cardinality</html:strong></html:em>) whenever there is a <fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-00KR.xml" title="bijection" addr="jms-00KR" type="local">bijection</fr:link> between them. In this case, we write <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A\cong  B]]></fr:tex> or <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathord {\#}{A}=\mathord {\#}{B}]]></fr:tex></html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jonmsterling.xml" title="Jon Sterling" addr="jonmsterling" type="local">Jon Sterling</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                  <fr:contributor>
                    <fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/marcelofiore.xml" title="Marcelo Fiore" addr="marcelofiore" type="local">Marcelo Fiore</fr:link>
                  </fr:contributor>
                </fr:authors>
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2024</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>1</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>23</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:addr>jms-00L1</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-00L1.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="examples of isomorphic sets">examples of <fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-00L0.xml" title="isomorphic sets" addr="jms-00L0" type="local">isomorphic sets</fr:link></fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>Example</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>A <fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-00KR.xml" title="bijection" addr="jms-00KR" type="local">bijection</fr:link> between finite sets is just a “relabeling” of its elements: for example, we have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left \{0,1\right \}\mathclose {}}\cong {\mathopen {}\left \{\mathsf {false},\mathsf {true}\right \}\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>. Isomorphism of infinite sets can be more confusing: for example, we have <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {N}\cong {\mathopen {}\left \{n:\mathbb {N}\,\middle \vert \,n>0\right \}\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {N}\cong \mathbb {Z}]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {N}\cong \mathbb {N}\times \mathbb {N}]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {N}\cong \mathbb {Q}]]></fr:tex>, and even <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left (\mathbb {N}\to \mathbb {N}\right )\mathclose {}}\cong \mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jonmsterling.xml" title="Jon Sterling" addr="jonmsterling" type="local">Jon Sterling</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                </fr:authors>
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2024</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>1</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>23</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:addr>jms-00L2</fr:addr>
                <fr:route>https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-00L2.xml</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="which bijection?">which <fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-00KR.xml" title="bijection" addr="jms-00KR" type="local">bijection</fr:link>?</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>Remark</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>Although we are speaking of “being isomorphic” as the property of there being a <fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-00KR.xml" title="bijection" addr="jms-00KR" type="local">bijection</fr:link> between them, in practice, it is almost <html:em>never</html:em> useful to know that there exists some undetermined <fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-00KR.xml" title="bijection" addr="jms-00KR" type="local">bijection</fr:link> between given sets; it is always important to know <html:em>which</html:em> <fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-00KR.xml" title="bijection" addr="jms-00KR" type="local">bijection</fr:link>. Indeed, we have seen in <fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-00KT.xml" title="counting bijections between finite sets" addr="jms-00KT" type="local">Proposition <fr:contextual-number addr="jms-00KT" /></fr:link> that there can be many distinct <fr:link href="https://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-00KR.xml" title="bijection" addr="jms-00KR" type="local">bijections</fr:link> between two sets.</html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
          </fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
      </fr:mainmatter>
    </fr:tree>
